Pwned1

Target IP: 192.168.246.95

Scanning



Looks like there are three TCP ports open on the target machine: FTP, SSH, and HTTP. FTP does not allow anonymous login; therefore, I will start my enumeration with HTTP application.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP
c
The webpage above is displayed when we browse to this application on a web-browser.

The attacker also left some hints behind.


The robots.txt contains the entries above.


The /hidden_text contains a wordlist of directories. I saved these entires in a wordlist for fuzzing.


Using BurpSuite, I fuzzed the directories inside the wordlist and received a hit on one directory: /pwned.vuln.


The /pwned.vuln webpage is shown above. There is a login form.

Viewing the source-code of this page is interesting as it contains the credentials ftpuser:B0ss_Pr!ncesS. Time to spray this against FTP.

Port 21: FTP

Using the credentials from above, I managed to login to the FTP and download the two files: id_rsa and note.txt.


The note.txt contains the message above about a new user called ariana. Maybe the id_rsa belongs to this user?

Exploitation


And now we have a foothold on the machine as ariana using the id_rsa.

Privilege Escalation


Another user exists called selena.


Apparently only selena can run the command above.


Now we know only selena can run messenger.sh binary as sudo, I used sudo -u selena /home/messenger.sh.


Then the username to send message to is selena, and the message is /bin/bash to spawn a shell as selena.


After upgrading my shell to an interactive Python shell, I did some more digging and found the message above.


Docker? Maybe we can escape out the resctricted enivronment and spawn an interactive shell?


And now I am root using the command docker run -v /:/mnt --rm -it alpine chroot /mnt sh.
